Instructions

The following questions are based on the following passage. You need to answer the questions based on the passage.
The wisdom of Birbal was unparalleled during the reign of Emperor Akbar. But Akbar’s brother-in-law was extremely jealous of him. He asked the Emperor to dispense with Birbal’s services and appoint him in his place. He gave ample assurance that he would prove to be more efficient and capable than Birbal. Before Akbar could take a decision on this matter, this news reached Birbal. Birbal resigned and left. Akbar’s brother-in-law was made the minister in place of Birbal. Akbar decided to test the new minister. He gave three hundred gold coins to him and said, “Spend these gold coins such that, I get a hundred gold coins here in this life; a hundred gold coins in the other world and another hundred gold coins neither here nor there.”The minister found the entire situation to be a maze of confusion and hopelessness. He spent sleepless nights worrying about how he would get himself out of this mess. Thinking in circles was making him go crazy. Eventually, on the advice of his wife, he sought Birbal’s help. Birbal said, “Just give me the gold coins. I shall handle the rest.”
Birbal walked the streets of the city holding the bag of gold coins in his hand. He noticed a rich merchant celebrating his son’s wedding. Birbal gave a hundred gold coins to him and bowed courteously saying, “Emperor Akbar sends you his good wishes and blessings for the wedding of your son. Please accept the gift he has sent.” The merchant felt honored that the king had sent a special messenger with such a precious gift. He honored Birbal and gave him a large number of expensive gifts and a bag of gold coins as a return gift for the king. Next, Birbal went to the area of the city where the poor people lived. There he bought food and clothing in exchange for a hundred gold coins and distributed them in the name of the Emperor. When he came back to town he organized a concert of music and dance. He spent a hundred gold coins on it.
The next day Birbal entered Akbar’s darbar and announced that he had done all that the king had asked his brother-in-law to do. The Emperor wanted to know how he had done it. Birbal repeated the sequences of all the events and then said, “The money I gave to the merchant for the wedding of his son - you have got back while on this earth. The money I spent on buying food and clothing for the poor - you will get it in the other world. The money I spent on the musical concert - you will get neither here nor there.” Akbar’s brother-in-law understood his mistake and resigned. Birbal got his place back.

Q 1
Report Bookmark

What Birbal did to the 300 gold coins which he got from the Akbar’s brother-in-law?



Solution

In the passage, it is mentioned that Akbar wanted to take the test of new minister so he gave 300 gold coins to him but later the new minister gave all the money to the Birbal so as to accept the challenge given by Akbar. Hence the option (c) will be correct.

In the following passage, certain words that may be either contextually or grammatically incorrect have been highlighted and numbered. For each highlighted word four alternatives are provided that could replace the highlighted word to make the given sentence both grammatically and contextually correct. A few days ago I said to a distinguished Bengali doctor of medicine, 'I know no German, yet if a translation of a German poet had moved me, I would go to the British Museum and find books in English that would tell me something of his life, and of the history of his thought. But though these prose translations from Rabindranath Tagore have rendered(1) my blood as nothing has for years, I shall not know anything of his life, and of the movements of thought that have made them possible, if some Indian traveler will not tell me.' It seemed to him natural that I should be moved, for he said, 'I read Rabindranath every day, to read one line of his is to forget all the troubles of the world.' I said, 'An Englishman living in London in the reign of Richard the Second had he been shown translations from Petrarch or from Dante, would have found no books to answer his questions, but would have questioned some Florentine banker or Lombard merchant as I question you. For all I know, so abundant and simple is this poetry, the new page(2) has been born in your country and I shall never know of it except by hearsay.' He answered, 'We have other poets, but none that are his equal; we call this the taint(4) of Rabindranath. No poet seems to me as famous in Europe as he is among us. He is as great in music as in poetry, and his songs are sung from the west of India into Burma wherever Bengali is spoken. He was already famous at nineteen when he wrote his first novel; and plays when he was but little older, are still played in Calcutta. I so much admire the intense(3) of his life; when he was very young he wrote much of natural objects, he would sit all day in his garden; from his twenty-fifth year or so to his thirty-fifth perhaps, when he had a great sorrow, he wrote the most beautiful love poetry in our language'; and then he said with deep emotion, 'words can never express what I owed at seventeen to his love poetry.

Q 9
Report Bookmark

Which of the following will replace the word marked (4) in the passage?



Solution

The meanings of the words are as follows.
Epoch: a particular period of time in history or a person's life.
Zenith: A time when something is most successful.
Nadir : The lowest or most unsuccessful point in a situation.
Acme: The point at which something is most highly developed.

The contextual meaning is most suitable for Epoch, hence it is the correct option.

(A) While the central Bank cannot take any decision unilaterally

Q 12
Report Bookmark

(A) The magistrate was sitting in the verandah of his tent
(B) I am aware that I shall be misunderstood and perhaps ridiculed by my colleagues
(C) Fortunately, or unfortunately, we cannot leave conscience to its own devices

Column (2):
(D) unless our lives are big enough and fine enough to warrant such a course.
(E) dispensing justice to the crowd awaiting their turns under the shade of a tree.
(F) when I attempt to discuss religion in any way.



Solution

After reading all the options it is evident that there are 3 correct sentences.
The magistrate was sitting in the verandah of his tent dispensing justice to the crowd awaiting their turns under the shade of a tree.
Fortunately, or unfortunately, we cannot leave conscience to its own devices unless our lives are big enough and fine enough to warrant such a course.
I am aware that I shall be misunderstood and perhaps ridiculed by my colleagues when I attempt to discuss religion in any way.
Each of the above sentences is correct. Hence option D is the correct answer.

Instructions

Read the following passage and answer the questions that follow:

It was a feature peculiar to the colonial wars of North America, that the toils and dangers of the wilderness were to be encountered before the adverse hosts could meet. A wide and apparently an impervious boundary of forests severed the possessions of the hostile provinces of France and England. The hardy colonist, and the trained European who fought at his side, frequently expended months in struggling against the rapids of the streams, or in effecting the rugged passes of the mountains, in quest of an opportunity to exhibit their courage in a more martial conflict. But, emulating the patience and self-denial of the practiced native warriors, they learned to overcome every difficulty; and it would seem that, in time, there was no recess of the woods so dark, nor any secret place so lovely, that it might claim exemption from the inroads of those who had pledged their blood to satiate their vengeance, or to uphold the cold and selfish policy of the distant monarchs of Europe.

Perhaps no district throughout the wide extent of the intermediate frontiers can furnish a livelier picture of the cruelty and fierceness of the savage warfare of those periods than the country which lies between the head waters of the Hudson and the adjacent lakes.

The facilities which nature had there offered to the march of the combatants were too obvious to be neglected. The lengthened sheet of the Champlain stretched from the frontiers of Canada, deep within the borders of the neighboring province of New York, forming a natural passage across half the distance that the French were compelled to master in order to strike their enemies. Near its southern termination, it received the contributions of another lake, whose waters were so limpid as to have been exclusively selected by the Jesuit missionaries to perform the typical purification of baptism, and to obtain for it the title of lake “du Saint Sacrement.” The less zealous English thought they conferred a sufficient honor on its unsullied fountains, when they bestowed the name of their reigning prince, the second of the house of Hanover. The two united to rob the untutored possessors of its wooded scenery of their native right to perpetuate its original appellation of “Horican.”

Winding its way among countless islands, and imbedded in mountains, the “holy lake” extended a dozen leagues still further to the south. With the high plain that there interposed itself to the further passage of the water, commenced a portage of as many miles, which conducted the adventurer to the banks of the Hudson, at a point where, with the usual obstructions of the rapids, or rifts, as they were then termed in the language of the country, the river became navigable to the tide.

While, in the pursuit of their daring plans of annoyance, the restless enterprise of the French even attempted the distant and difficult gorges of the Alleghany, it may easily be imagined that their proverbial acuteness would not overlook the natural advantages of the district we have just described. It became, emphatically, the bloody arena, in which most of the battles for the mastery of the colonies were contested. Forts were erected at the different points that commanded the facilities of the route, and were taken and retaken, razed and rebuilt, as victory alighted on the hostile banners. While the husbandman shrank back from the dangerous passes, within the safer boundaries of the more ancient settlements, armies larger than those that had often disposed of the scepters of the mother countries, were seen to bury themselves in these forests, whence they rarely returned but in skeleton bands, that were haggard with care or dejected by defeat. Though the arts of peace were unknown to this fatal region, its forests were alive with men; its shades and glens rang with the sounds of martial music, and the echoes of its mountains threw back the laugh, or repeated the wanton cry, of many a gallant and reckless youth, as he hurried by them, in the noontide of his spirits, to slumber in a long night of forgetfulness.

It was in this scene of strife and bloodshed that the incidents we shall attempt to relate occurred, during the third year of the war which England and France last waged for the possession of a country that neither was destined to retain.

The imbecility of her military leaders abroad, and the fatal want of energy in her councils at home, had lowered the character of Great Britain from the proud elevation on which it had been placed by the talents and enterprise of her former warriors and statesmen. No longer dreaded by her enemies, her servants were fast losing the confidence of self-respect. In this mortifying abasement, the colonists, though innocent of her imbecility, and too humble to be the agents of her blunders, were but the natural participators. They had recently seen a chosen army from that country, which, reverencing as a mother, they had blindly believed invincible—an army led by a chief who had been selected from a crowd of trained warriors, for his rare military endowments, disgracefully routed by a handful of French and Indians, and only saved from annihilation by the coolness and spirit of a Virginian boy, whose riper fame has since diffused itself, with the steady influence of moral truth, to the uttermost confines of Christendom. A wide frontier had been laid naked by this unexpected disaster, and more substantial evils were preceded by a thousand fanciful and imaginary dangers. The alarmed colonists believed that the yells of the savages mingled with every fitful gust of wind that issued from the interminable forests of the west. The terrific character of their merciless enemies increased immeasurably the natural horrors of warfare. Numberless recent massacres were still vivid in their recollections; nor was there any ear in the provinces so deaf as not to have drunk in with avidity the narrative of some fearful tale of midnight murder, in which the natives of the forests were the principal and barbarous actors. As the credulous and excited traveler related the hazardous chances of the wilderness, the blood of the timid curdled with terror, and mothers cast anxious glances even at those children which slumbered within the security of the largest towns. In short, the magnifying influence of fear began to set at naught the calculations of reason, and to render those who should have remembered their manhood, the slaves of the basest passions. Even the most confident and the stoutest hearts began to think the issue of the contest was becoming doubtful; and that abject class was hourly increasing in numbers, who thought they foresaw all the possessions of the English crown in America subdued by their Christian foes, or laid waste by the inroads of their relentless allies.

However, option C states that France and England are separated by thick forests (not the provinces). A wide frontier had been laid naked by this unexpected disaster, and more substantial evils were preceded by a thousand fanciful and imaginary dangers. The terrific character of their merciless enemies increased immeasurably the natural horrors of warfare. Numberless recent massacres were still vivid in their recollections; nor was there any ear in the provinces so deaf as not to have drunk in with avidity the narrative of some fearful tale of midnight murder, in which the natives of the forests were the principal and barbarous actors. As the credulous and excited traveler related the hazardous chances of the wilderness, the blood of the timid curdled with terror, and mothers cast anxious glances even at those children which slumbered within the security of the largest towns. In short, the magnifying influence of fear began to set at naught the calculations of reason, and to render those who should have remembered their manhood, the slaves of the basest passions. Even the most confident and the stoutest hearts began to think the issue of the contest was becoming doubtful; and that abject class was hourly increasing in numbers, who thought they foresaw all the possessions of the English crown in America subdued by their Christian foes, or laid waste by the inroads of their relentless allies.

Though the arts of peace were unknown to this fatal region, its forests were alive with men; its shades and glens rang with the sounds of martial music, and the echoes of its mountains threw back the laugh, or repeated the wanton cry, of many a gallant and reckless youth, as he hurried by them, in the noontide of his spirits, to slumber in a long night of forgetfulness.

It was in this scene of strife and bloodshed that the incidents we shall attempt to relate occurred, during the third year of the war which England and France last waged for the possession of a country that neither was destined to retain.

Numberless recent massacres were still vivid in their recollections; nor was there any ear in the provinces so deaf as not to have drunk in with avidity the narrative of some fearful tale of midnight murder, in which the natives of the forests were the principal and barbarous actors. As the credulous and excited traveler related the hazardous chances of the wilderness, the blood of the timid curdled with terror, and mothers cast anxious glances even at those children which slumbered within the security of the largest towns. In short, the magnifying influence of fear began to set at naught the calculations of reason, and to render those who should have remembered their manhood, the slaves of the basest passions. Even the most confident and the stoutest hearts began to think the issue of the contest was becoming doubtful; and that abject class was hourly increasing in numbers, who thought they foresaw all the possessions of the English crown in America subdued by their Christian foes, or laid waste by the inroads of their relentless allies.

Instructions

Read the following passage and answer the questions that follow:

It was a feature peculiar to the colonial wars of North America, that the toils and dangers of the wilderness were to be encountered before the adverse hosts could meet. A wide and apparently an impervious boundary of forests severed the possessions of the hostile provinces of France and England. The hardy colonist, and the trained European who fought at his side, frequently expended months in struggling against the rapids of the streams, or in effecting the rugged passes of the mountains, in quest of an opportunity to exhibit their courage in a more martial conflict. But, emulating the patience and self-denial of the practiced native warriors, they learned to overcome every difficulty; and it would seem that, in time, there was no recess of the woods so dark, nor any secret place so lovely, that it might claim exemption from the inroads of those who had pledged their blood to satiate their vengeance, or to uphold the cold and selfish policy of the distant monarchs of Europe.

Perhaps no district throughout the wide extent of the intermediate frontiers can furnish a livelier picture of the cruelty and fierceness of the savage warfare of those periods than the country which lies between the head waters of the Hudson and the adjacent lakes.

The facilities which nature had there offered to the march of the combatants were too obvious to be neglected. The lengthened sheet of the Champlain stretched from the frontiers of Canada, deep within the borders of the neighboring province of New York, forming a natural passage across half the distance that the French were compelled to master in order to strike their enemies. Near its southern termination, it received the contributions of another lake, whose waters were so limpid as to have been exclusively selected by the Jesuit missionaries to perform the typical purification of baptism, and to obtain for it the title of lake “du Saint Sacrement.” The less zealous English thought they conferred a sufficient honor on its unsullied fountains, when they bestowed the name of their reigning prince, the second of the house of Hanover. The two united to rob the untutored possessors of its wooded scenery of their native right to perpetuate its original appellation of “Horican.”

Winding its way among countless islands, and imbedded in mountains, the “holy lake” extended a dozen leagues still further to the south. With the high plain that there interposed itself to the further passage of the water, commenced a portage of as many miles, which conducted the adventurer to the banks of the Hudson, at a point where, with the usual obstructions of the rapids, or rifts, as they were then termed in the language of the country, the river became navigable to the tide.

While, in the pursuit of their daring plans of annoyance, the restless enterprise of the French even attempted the distant and difficult gorges of the Alleghany, it may easily be imagined that their proverbial acuteness would not overlook the natural advantages of the district we have just described. It became, emphatically, the bloody arena, in which most of the battles for the mastery of the colonies were contested. Forts were erected at the different points that commanded the facilities of the route, and were taken and retaken, razed and rebuilt, as victory alighted on the hostile banners. While the husbandman shrank back from the dangerous passes, within the safer boundaries of the more ancient settlements, armies larger than those that had often disposed of the scepters of the mother countries, were seen to bury themselves in these forests, whence they rarely returned but in skeleton bands, that were haggard with care or dejected by defeat. Though the arts of peace were unknown to this fatal region, its forests were alive with men; its shades and glens rang with the sounds of martial music, and the echoes of its mountains threw back the laugh, or repeated the wanton cry, of many a gallant and reckless youth, as he hurried by them, in the noontide of his spirits, to slumber in a long night of forgetfulness.

It was in this scene of strife and bloodshed that the incidents we shall attempt to relate occurred, during the third year of the war which England and France last waged for the possession of a country that neither was destined to retain.

The imbecility of her military leaders abroad, and the fatal want of energy in her councils at home, had lowered the character of Great Britain from the proud elevation on which it had been placed by the talents and enterprise of her former warriors and statesmen. No longer dreaded by her enemies, her servants were fast losing the confidence of self-respect. In this mortifying abasement, the colonists, though innocent of her imbecility, and too humble to be the agents of her blunders, were but the natural participators. They had recently seen a chosen army from that country, which, reverencing as a mother, they had blindly believed invincible—an army led by a chief who had been selected from a crowd of trained warriors, for his rare military endowments, disgracefully routed by a handful of French and Indians, and only saved from annihilation by the coolness and spirit of a Virginian boy, whose riper fame has since diffused itself, with the steady influence of moral truth, to the uttermost confines of Christendom. A wide frontier had been laid naked by this unexpected disaster, and more substantial evils were preceded by a thousand fanciful and imaginary dangers. The alarmed colonists believed that the yells of the savages mingled with every fitful gust of wind that issued from the interminable forests of the west. The terrific character of their merciless enemies increased immeasurably the natural horrors of warfare. Numberless recent massacres were still vivid in their recollections; nor was there any ear in the provinces so deaf as not to have drunk in with avidity the narrative of some fearful tale of midnight murder, in which the natives of the forests were the principal and barbarous actors. As the credulous and excited traveler related the hazardous chances of the wilderness, the blood of the timid curdled with terror, and mothers cast anxious glances even at those children which slumbered within the security of the largest towns. In short, the magnifying influence of fear began to set at naught the calculations of reason, and to render those who should have remembered their manhood, the slaves of the basest passions. Even the most confident and the stoutest hearts began to think the issue of the contest was becoming doubtful; and that abject class was hourly increasing in numbers, who thought they foresaw all the possessions of the English crown in America subdued by their Christian foes, or laid waste by the inroads of their relentless allies.

In a mixture of 27 litres, The ratio of water and alcohol in the mixture is 7:2 respectively.
Let’s assume the quantity of water and alcohol in the mixture is 7a and 2a respectively.
7a+2a = 27
9a = 27
Quantity of water initially = 7a = 21
Quantity of alcohol initially = 2a = 6

Q 109
Report Bookmark

An open tap can fill a bucket of 40 litres in one hour, if in every 5 minutes a mug of water removes 2 litres of water from the bucket, then find the time taken to fill the bucket completely if all are working together.



Solution

According to the question,
Efficiency of tap = 40/60 = ⅔ litres water per minute so filled in 5 minutes = (2/3) x 5 = 10/3
Water removed by mug in 5 minutes = - 2 litres( - minus sign as negative work done)
So total work done if working together in 5 minutes = (10/3 - 2 = 4/3 litre water per 5 minute.
So water filled in first 120 minutes = (120/5) x (4/3) = 32 litres, remaining volume to fill = 8 litres 

So water filled in next 25 minutes = (25/5) x (4/3) = 20/3, remaining volume = 8 - (20/3) = 4/3 litres 

Now to fill 4/3 litres of water only tap will be working so time taken = 4323\dfrac{\frac{4}{3}}{\frac{2}{3}}32​34​​ = 2 minutes

So time taken to fill the bucket = 120 + 25 + 2  = 147 minutes.

Q 110
Report Bookmark

A man invests Rs 30,000 in simple interest for 3 years at 8% p.a and at the end of three years, he invests the three-fourth of the amount(principal+interest) received after 3 years in compound interest for one year at 12% rate. so find the difference between the simple interest received after 3 years and compound interest received after one year by him.



Solution

According to the question,
For simple interest,
Principal = 30000, rate = 8% time = 3 years
SI = PRT100\frac{PRT}{100}100PRT​
SI = 30000×8×3100\frac{30000 \times 8 \times 3}{100}10030000×8×3​, solving this we get,
SI = 7200
Amount = 30000 + 7200 = 37200

For compound interest,
Principal = ¾ of 37200 = 27900, rate = 12% and time = 1 years
CI = P(1+r/100) - P,
Or =27900(1 + 12/100) - 27900
Or = 27900[112−100100\frac{112 - 100}{100}100112−100​]
Or = 27900 x 12/100,
Compound interest = 3348

Hence the difference = 7200 - 3348 = Rs 3852.

Q 126

Which of the following statements will hold a true relation for both the given conclusions ‘X@T and ‘Q@U’?



Solution

From the statement (a) we have;

X≤V>U; O≥P<Q=V=T, from this we X≤T and Q>U but here both conclusions are not satisfying.

From the statement (b) we have

T<O>G≥U; Q≥X≥N

From this we will not get the exact relation between X and T and Q and U.

From the statement (c) we have,

Q≥R=X; T<R>U

From this, we get, Q>U and X>T. Hence both conclusions are true for the given statement.

From the statement (d) we have,

Q≤D≥K≥X; T=D≤U,

From this, we get, X≤T and Q≤T. So, both conclusions will not hold true for the given statement.

Hence, option (c) is correct.

Six girls Kavita, Sita, Anita, Vinita, Unita, and Elita are standing on the different stairs of a staircase of their hostel. The staircase has six stairs. The lowermost stair is numbered as one and topmost stair is numbered as six. Three girls are travelling by bus but not particularly the same bus and the remaining three are travelling by train but not particularly the same train.
Conditions::
- The girls whose name starts with a vowel are standing on an odd numbered stair and the remaining are standing on an even numbered stair.
- Elita is not standing on the first and third numbered stair. More than one girl is standing between Elita and Unita.
- One girl is standing between Anita who is travelling by Rajdhani Express and the one who is travelling by Volvo Bus.
- Two girls are standing between the one who is travelling by Shatabdi Express and the one who is travelling by Volvo Bus.
- The girl whose name has the least number of vowels is standing on the stair numbered as the same as the number of letters in her name.
- The one who is travelling by Shatabdi Express is not standing on the second numbered stair. The one who is travelling by Shatabdi Express and the one who is travelling by Deluxe Bus is standing on the consecutive stairs.
- No one is standing between Unita and Vinita who is travelling by Duronto Express.
- One girl is travelling by Sleeper Bus.

Q 132
Report Bookmark

How many girls are standing between Vinita and Kavita?



Solution

The girl whose name is having the least number of vowels is standing on the stair number which is the same as the number of letters in her name.

As per the above-given condition, here Sita will be on stair number four. Because it has the least number of vowels and the number of letters in the name is four. So she will be on the fourth stair.

Those girls whose name starts with vowels are standing on an odd number stair and the remaining are standing on an even number stair. Elita is not standing on the first and third number stair.

As per the condition, Elita will be on the fifth number stair.

More than one girl is standing between Elita and Unita.

As per the condition, Unita will be on the first stair. Because She will be on an odd stair.

One girl is standing between Anita who is travelling by Rajdhani Express and the one who is travelling by Volvo Bus.

Now Anita will be on the third stair. Because as per the condition, Those girls whose name starts with vowels are standing on an odd number stair.

Here as per the condition, “One girl is standing between Anita who is travelling by Rajdhani Express and the one who is travelling by Volvo Bus.” So there are two possible places for Volvo Bus which are mentioned in Case(i) and Case(ii) below.

Two girls are standing between the one who is travelling by Shatabdi Express and the one who is travelling by Volvo Bus. The one who is travelling by Shatabdi Express is not standing on the second number stair.

Here Case(ii) given below will be eliminated. Because as per the condition, Shatabdi Express cannot be placed in the second number stair.

The one who is travelling by Shatabdi Express and the one who is travelling by Deluxe Bus is standing on the consecutive stairs.

No one is standing between Unita and Vinita who is travelling by Duronto Express.

One girl is travelling by Sleeper Bus.

Now only one girl Kavita is remaining which will be placed on the sixth number stair.

Therefore, We got the final arrangement which is given below.

According to the above arrangement,Three girls are standing between Vinita and Kavita.
Hence, option b is the correct answer.

Q 168
Report Bookmark

N is from which of the following country?



Solution

The age of Q is a prime number but he is not the youngest among them.

As per the above given condition, The age of Q cannot be 13 years. So there are two possible ages for Q which are 23 years and 29 years given in Case(i) and Case(ii) below.

The difference between the ages of Q and M is 5 years.

In Case(i), as per the above given condition, The age of M will be 18 years.

In Case(ii), as per the above given condition, The age of M will be 34 years.

The number of people born before M and after L who is from China is the same. One person was born between L and S.

Apply the above given conditions in both cases.

The difference between the ages of S and P is the same as the difference between the ages of M and R who is from India.

In Case(i), as per the above given condition, 42 years is not possible as the age of P. So The possible age of P will be 34 years and 13 years. If we assume the age of P is 34 years. Then the difference between the ages of S and P will be 5 years. We can say that the age of R will be either 23 years or 13 years. But 23 years is already taken by Q. So when the age of P is 34 years. Then the age of R will be 13 years. If we assume the age of P is 13 years. Then the difference between the ages of S and P will be 16 years. We can say that the age of R will be either 2 years or 34 years. Here 2 years is not possible. So when the age of P is 13 years. Then the age of R will be 34 years. Finally we got two possible ages of P which will generate two possible ages of R given below in Case(i)(a) and Case(i)(b).

In Case(ii), as per the above given condition, The possible ages of P will be 18 years, 38 years and 42 years. Through these possible ages of P, we will get the possible ages of R which will be 29 years, 39 years, 9 years, 5 years and 59 years. But none of the age is possible here for R. So this case is eliminated.

Three people were born between the one who is from India and the one who is from Russia.

Apply the above given condition in both cases.

The one who is from Mexico was born exactly between the one who is from Russia and the one whose age is a prime number. Q is not from Mexico.

Apply the above given condition in both cases.

More than two people were born between the one who is from Mexico and the one who is from Japan.

In Case(i)(a), the above given condition is not applicable. So this case is eliminated.

In Case(i)(b), as per the above given condition, the person whose age is 42 years is from Japan. There is only one person namely N is remaining which will be placed in the blank space.

Now only two countries Italy and Spain are remaining which will be placed in the blank spaces in either or form.

Therefore we got the final arrangement which is given below.

According to the above arrangement, N is from Japan.
Hence, option c is the correct answer.

Four among the five given below forms a group. Which of the following does not belong to that group?



Solution

Only two people got more marks than D.
> > D > > > > Eq.(1)
A got more marks than D.
A > D Eq.(2)
D does not get more marks than F.
F > D Eq.(3)
Put Eq.(2) and Eq.(3) in Eq.(1).
Here F and A got more marks than D. But we don't know who got the highest. So we get two possible cases which are given below as Case(i) and Case(ii).
Case(i)
F > A > D > > > >
Case(ii)
A > F > D > > > >

The number of people who got more marks than A is the same as the number of people who got less marks than C.
In Case(i),If A gets the second highest mark. Then C will get the second lowest marks as per the above given condition.
In Case(ii),If A gets the highest mark. Then C will get the lowest marks as per the above given condition.
Case(i)
F > A > D > > > C >
Case(ii)
A > F > D > > > > C

B got more marks than G but less marks than F who likes banana.
F(banana) > B > G Eq.(4)
G got less marks than E who likes apple.
E(apple) > G Eq.(5)
At least one person got less marks than G.
From Eq.(4) and Eq.(5), we can say that F, E and B got more marks than G.
In Case(i), G got least marks which is not possible as per the above given condition. So this case is eliminated.
In Case(ii), The given condition is applicable.
Case(i)
F(banana) > A > D > E(apple)/B > E(apple)/B > C > G
Case(ii)
A > F(banana) > D > E(apple)/B > E(apple)/B > G > C

The one who got second lowest marks likes mango.
Case(ii)
A > F(banana) > D > E(apple)/B > E(apple)/B > G(mango) > C

The one who likes cherry got more marks than the one who likes banana.
cherry > banana
Case(ii)
A(cherry) > F(banana) > D > E(apple)/B > E(apple)/B > G(mango) > C

The one who likes orange got more marks than the one who likes apple. B does not like orange.
orange > apple
Case(ii)
A(cherry) > F(banana) > D(orange) > E(apple)/B > E(apple)/B > G(mango) > C

The one who likes guava got less marks than the one who likes grapes.
grapes > guava
Case(ii)
A(cherry) > F(banana) > D(orange) > E(apple)/B(grapes) > E(apple)/B(grapes) > G(mango) > C(guava)

Therefore we got the final arrangement which is given below.
A(cherry) > F(banana) > D(orange) > E(apple)/B(grapes) > E(apple)/B(grapes) > G(mango) > C(guava)

According to the above arrangement, ranks A, D, F and C can be determined exactly. But the rank of E cannot be determined exactly. So this is the odd one.
Hence, option e is the correct answer.


Instructions

Eight boxes P, Q, R, S, W, X, Y and Z are arranged one above from top to bottom but necessarily in the same order. Each box is coloured with different colours namely red, blue, yellow, pink, white, green, orange and purple but not necessarily in the same order.
More than two boxes are placed between the box which is coloured with red colour and the box which is coloured with yellow colour. Five boxes are placed between the box which is coloured with yellow colour and the box which is coloured with orange colour. Pink coloured box is placed exactly between the box which is coloured with red colour and the box which is coloured with orange colour. Box Z is not coloured with pink colour. The number of boxes placed above the box which is pink colour and the number of boxes placed below the box which is purple colour is the same. Three boxes are placed between the box which is coloured with blue colour and the box which is coloured with green colour. Four boxes are placed between box Q and box W. One box is placed between box W and box R. The number of boxes placed above box P and the number of boxes placed below box Y is the same. Two boxes are placed between box R and box Y. Box Q is placed above box R which is coloured by red colour. No box is placed between box Y and box S.

Q 184
Report Bookmark

From which colour Box Z is coloured?



Solution

Four boxes are placed between box Q and box W.

The above given condition will generate two possible cases which are given in Case(i) and Case(ii) below.

One box is placed between box W and box R.

In Case(i), R is possible above W and below W as per the condition which is given below in Case(i)(a) and Case(i)(b) below.

In Case(ii), R is possible above W and below W as per the condition which is given below in Case(ii)(a) and Case(ii)(b) below.

Box Q is placed above box R which is coloured by red colour.

In Case(i)(a) and Case(i)(b), Box Q is placed above box R. But in Case(ii)(a) and Case(ii)(b), Box Q is not placed above box R. So Case(ii)(a) and Case(ii)(b) will be eliminated.

Two boxes are placed between box R and box Y.

According to the above given condition, In Case(i)(a), box Y is possible below box R. But in Case(i)(a), box Y is possible above box R.

No box is placed between box Y and box S. The number of boxes placed above box P and the number of boxes placed below box Y is the same.

Here in Case(i)(b), “The number of boxes placed above box P and the number of boxes placed below box Y is the same.” is not applicable. So this case is eliminated.

Now only two boxes namely box Z and box X are remaining which can be placed in either or form in the remaining Case(i)(a).

More than two boxes are placed between the box which is coloured with red colour and the box which is coloured with yellow colour. Five boxes are placed between the box which is coloured with yellow colour and the box which is coloured with orange colour.

Pink coloured box is placed exactly between the box which is coloured with red colour and the box which is coloured with orange colour. Box Z is not coloured with pink colour.

After combining the above given both the conditions, we can say that box X is coloured with pink colour.

The number of boxes placed above the box which is pink colour and the number of boxes placed below the box which is purple colour is the same.

There are two boxes above the pink coloured box. Then as per the above given condition, there will be two boxes below purple colour box.

Three boxes are placed between the box which is coloured with blue colour and the box which is coloured with green colour.

As per the above given condition, Here Q or Z can be either coloured with blue or green colour.

Now only one colour which is white is remaining. It will be placed in the blank space.

Therefore, we got the final arrangement which is given below.

According to the above arrangement, Box Z is coloured with either blue or green colour.
Hence, option c is the correct answer.

Q 196
Report Bookmark

What is the code for the word “Winter”?



Solution

Code for first letter ⇒ The reverse letter of the last letter of the word.
Code for last letter ⇒ The reverse letter of the first letter of the word.
For number ⇒ The number of letters in a word is even. Then multiply it by 2. Else the number of letters will be multiplied by 3.
For symbol ⇒ The second last letter of the word is vowel then @ symbol will be there. Else # symbol will be there.
For example, the word “Relax”, First and last letter reverse will be ‘I’ and ‘C’. After interchanging these will be “CI”. Here the number of letters is five. So it will be 5*3 = 15. Second last letter of the word is ‘a’ which is a vowel. So code for this will be @. Thus the code for the word “Relax” will be “CI@15”.

Code for the word “Winter” will be “ID@12”.
Hence, option d is the correct answer.
